Since the URL is ip/remedy-incidents, search for that route in the codebase:
In VS Code:
Ctrl + Shift + F  →  search for "remedy-incidents"
This will lead you to either a Controller or a Route definition

Step 2 — What to look for in results
You'll likely find one of these patterns:
// MVC Controller
[Route("remedy-incidents")]
public class RemedyIncidentsController : Controller

// OR a method inside a controller
[HttpGet("remedy-incidents")]
public IActionResult Index()

Step 3 — Find the actual UI page
Once you find the controller method, look at what it returns:
return View();           // → look in /Views/RemedyIncidents/Index.cshtml
return View("PageName"); // → look in /Views/RemedyIncidents/PageName.cshtml
The .cshtml file is your actual page where the options/dropdown is built.

Step 4 — Find the JS file
Inside that .cshtml, look for:
html<script src="..."></script>
That JS file is where the options click logic and auto-fill lives — which you'll reuse for USE THIS.


✅ The .cshtml file
✅ The .js file
